{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505137"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2408"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2408"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.07,0.03,0.29,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103090"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2408"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2021-02-18T03:50:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-04T22:34:22+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-10-07T10:25:13+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-27 11:32:16"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2408"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"20237"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"31"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85554"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"3026"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"3205"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4457"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35827"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85554"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103090"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman is admitted to a psychiatric inpatient facility with severe suicidal ideation, having made specific plans for overdose via paracetamol. For four months she has been experiencing low mood, anhedonia, sleep disturbances, poor appetite and feelings of low self-worth. She has lost 7kg weight, barely eats and drinks to sustain herself and still is actively suicidal. She has also expressed paranoid delusions, believing that her mother-in-law is poisoning her children. She gave birth to her second child six weeks ago. She has no homicidal thoughts. She comes from a supportive home environment with her husband and two daughters, aged two years and six weeks. The infant is still being breast-fed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sertraline","Olanzapine","Lamotrigine","Combined SSRI and antipsychotic","Electroconvulsive therapy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPeripartum depression (PPD) is an important consideration in the postnatal period. This patient presents with features suggestive of severe PPD which may be diagnosed if onset of symptoms occur during pregnancy or in the four week post delivery, with imminent risk given her poor self care, active suicidal ideation and psychotic features. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases of severe PPD, especially when the woman refuses to eat or drink and/or there is a high suicide risk, \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectroconvulsive therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (ECT) is the first line therapy. This is appropriate in this case as her depression is so severe that it is interfering with her activities of daily living, and she has dependent children to care for. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombination of an antidepressant and antipsychotic\u003C/strong\u003E would be a suitable alternative if the patient were at lower risk and could be safely monitored as an inpatient while the treatment became effective. In some circumstances, depending on patient and family preference, the combination of an antidepressant and antipsychotic may be preferred. However, in this case there is significant risk to this patient if not treated imminently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertraline\u003C/strong\u003E may be suitable in mild peripartum depression without psychotic features but caution needs to be taken (as with all SSRIs) to monitor for increased agitation and suicidal ideation. Sertraline is poorly expressed in breastmilk and therefore is not usually detected in the infants serum and is considered a safe medication for use in breastfeeding women. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlanzapine\u003C/strong\u003E is an antipsychotic that can be used to manage psychotic symptoms, but it does not address the underlying depressive symptoms and would not be sufficient as monotherapy in this case. In breastfeeding women olanzapine can be used without interruption to feeding with minimal short term side effects reported in infants. Breastfed infants of mothers administered olanzapine should be monitored for drowsiness, poor feeding, tremors and movement disorders. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELamotrigine\u003C/strong\u003E is a mood stabiliser often used in bipolar disorder but is not first-line for severe depression with psychotic features, especially in the context of imminent risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined SSRI and antipsychotic\u003C/strong\u003E therapy can be effective for severe depression with psychotic features, but these medications take time to become effective, and this patient requires immediate intervention due to the high risk of suicide.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medications including antipsychotic medication and SSRIs have a response time of up to 4 weeks","Where there is imminent serious risk to self or others including dependents, ECT is first line due to the need for immediate response to treatment."],"references":["Centre of Perinatal Excellence (COPE). Postpartum Psychosis: A Guide for Health Professionals [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): COPE; 2017 [cited 2025 May 19]. Available from: https://www.cope.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Postpartum-Psychosis_Health-Prof-Fact-Sheet.pdf","South Australian Perinatal Practice Guidelines. Psychotic Disorders in the Perinatal Period (Schizophrenia, Bipolar Disorder and Postpartum Psychosis) [Internet]. Adelaide (AU): SA Health; 2020 [cited 2025 May 19]. Available from: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/8fbf20004eeda373b123b36a7ac0d6e4/Psychotic+Disorders+in+the+Perinatal+Period+(Schizophrenia+Bipolar+Disorder+and+Postpartum+Psychosis)_PPG_v6_0.pdf?MOD=AJPERES","Nonpharmacological therapies for psychiatric illness [Internet]. eTG Complete. 2017. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Psychiatric conditions in pregnancy and the postpartum[Internet]. eTG Complete. 2017. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Drugs and Lactation Database (LactMed). Sertraline. Bethesda (MD): National Library of Medicine (US); [cited 2025 May 19]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK501073/","Drugs and Lactation Database (LactMed). Olanzapine. Bethesda (MD): National Library of Medicine (US); [cited 2025 May 19]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK501296/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"8